eligious education. Her analysis reveals the contradictions and nuances of a policy driven by a wide range of motives and implemented by a diverse group of government authorities, illustrating how Israeli policies produced a co-opted religious establishment lacking popular support and paved the way for a daring challenge by a grassroots Islamist Movement since the 1980s. As part of a wider debate on early Israeli history, she challenges the idea that Israeli policy was part of a greater monolithic policy toward the Arab minority.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aIslamxRelationsxJudaism. 0aJudaismxRelationsxIslam. 0aMuslimszIsrael. 0aPalestinian ArabsxGovernment policyzIsrael. 0aPalestinian ArabszIsraelxPolitics and governmenty20th century. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Islam. 7aRELIGION / Islam / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791490068423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791490068/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles